<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="323" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,531,1051,1114]" box="[151,284,1087,1114]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">
<figureCitation box="[151,280,1087,1114]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–55" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-142@23.[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 49–55. 49. Dorsal view of male of Megachile sp. 1. 50. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male of Megachile sp. 1. 51. Apical margin of clypeus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 52. Ventral view of front tarsus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 53. Apical part of antenna of male of Megachile sp. 2. 43. 54. Front coxal spine of male of Megachile sp. 2. 55. Mandibles and clypeus of female of Megachile sp. 3." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494671" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494671/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Figs 51–54</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1159,1725]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1159,1185]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Male</emphasis>
: Small-sized 
<taxonomicName box="[417,566,1159,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Eutricharaea">
<emphasis box="[417,566,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Eutricharaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
characterized as follows: Integument dark, except the following body parts, which are orange: all femora and tarsi, front coxa, all sternites, antennae except scape and pedicel, parts of mandibles and clypeus, latero-inferior parts of T1 and T2. Front legs modified as follows: front coxa with comparatively long and acute, triangular spine (
<figureCitation box="[516,598,1267,1294]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–55" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-142@23.[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 49–55. 49. Dorsal view of male of Megachile sp. 1. 50. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male of Megachile sp. 1. 51. Apical margin of clypeus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 52. Ventral view of front tarsus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 53. Apical part of antenna of male of Megachile sp. 2. 43. 54. Front coxal spine of male of Megachile sp. 2. 55. Mandibles and clypeus of female of Megachile sp. 3." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494671" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494671/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Fig. 54</figureCitation>
), anterior surface of coxa glabrous, shiny, nearly impunctate, without patch of orange setae. Front tarsi yellowish white, ventral side of segments 2 and 3 with black maculation (
<figureCitation box="[1284,1369,1303,1330]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–55" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-142@23.[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 49–55. 49. Dorsal view of male of Megachile sp. 1. 50. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male of Megachile sp. 1. 51. Apical margin of clypeus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 52. Ventral view of front tarsus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 53. Apical part of antenna of male of Megachile sp. 2. 43. 54. Front coxal spine of male of Megachile sp. 2. 55. Mandibles and clypeus of female of Megachile sp. 3." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494671" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494671/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Fig. 52</figureCitation>
). Last antennal segment distinctly broadened, spatulate (
<figureCitation box="[714,798,1339,1366]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–55" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-142@23.[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 49–55. 49. Dorsal view of male of Megachile sp. 1. 50. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male of Megachile sp. 1. 51. Apical margin of clypeus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 52. Ventral view of front tarsus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 53. Apical part of antenna of male of Megachile sp. 2. 43. 54. Front coxal spine of male of Megachile sp. 2. 55. Mandibles and clypeus of female of Megachile sp. 3." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494671" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494671/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
). The most distinctive feature is the apical margin of the clypeus, with two rounded teeth separated by a deep emargination (
<figureCitation box="[918,1002,1375,1402]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–55" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-142@23.[181,1406,453,1845]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 49–55. 49. Dorsal view of male of Megachile sp. 1. 50. Dorsal view of mesosoma and head of male of Megachile sp. 1. 51. Apical margin of clypeus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 52. Ventral view of front tarsus of male of Megachile sp. 2. 53. Apical part of antenna of male of Megachile sp. 2. 43. 54. Front coxal spine of male of Megachile sp. 2. 55. Mandibles and clypeus of female of Megachile sp. 3." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5494671" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5494671/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). Preapical carina of T6 with 10 acute teeth and with medial emargination. Genitalia as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Praz &amp; Al-Shahat &amp; Gadallah, 2021" authorityName="Praz &amp; Al-Shahat &amp; Gadallah" authorityYear="2021" box="[725,1045,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufomandibularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[725,1045,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Megachile rufomandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1052,1140,1411,1437]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1052,1140,1411,1437]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, gonostylus apically bifid, with a short preapical lobe. The structure of the genitalia is reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName authority="Praz &amp; Al-Shahat &amp; Gadallah, 2021" authorityName="Praz &amp; Al-Shahat &amp; Gadallah" authorityYear="2021" box="[1012,1336,1447,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufomandibularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1012,1336,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Megachile rufomandibularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1345,1436,1447,1473]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1345,1436,1447,1473]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kohl" authorityYear="1906" box="[199,312,1484,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="naevia">
<emphasis box="[199,312,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">M. naevia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, thus places this species in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kohl" authorityYear="1906" box="[666,741,1484,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="naevia">
<emphasis box="[666,741,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">naevia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group. This species would run to 
<taxonomicName authority="Cockerell 1931" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1931" box="[1128,1436,1483,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="admixta">
<emphasis box="[1128,1256,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">M. admixta</emphasis>
Cockerell 
<quantity box="[1380,1436,1483,1509]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.904739999999999" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" unit="in" value="1931.0">1931</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in the key by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pasteels, J. J." box="[302,477,1519,1546]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" pagination="1 - 579" refId="ref24842" refString="Pasteels, J. J. (1965) Revision des Megachilidae (Hymenoptera Apoidea) de l'Afrique Noire. I. Les genres Creightonella [sic], Chalicodoma et Megachile (s. str.). Zoologische wetenschappen / Koninklijk Museum voor Midden-Afrika, Tervuren, Belgie, 137, ix + 1 - 579." type="journal article" year="1965">Pasteels (1965)</bibRefCitation>
; both species appear to share numerous characteristics, especially the short vertex, the emarginate clypeus, the strong carina under the front femur and the short vertex, a combination of features that is otherwise unusual in 
<taxonomicName box="[390,539,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Eutricharaea">
<emphasis box="[390,539,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Eutricharaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1159,1725]" box="[199,722,1627,1654]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1627,1653]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Female</emphasis>
: Unknown (possibly 
<taxonomicName box="[528,708,1627,1654]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undefined-3">
<emphasis box="[528,646,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Megachile</emphasis>
sp. 3
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
